{"id":"astro-ph/0210209","submitter":"Pier Stefano Corasaniti","authors":"P.S. Corasaniti, B.A. Bassett, C. Ungarelli, E.J. Copeland","title":"Model-independent dark energy differentiation with the ISW effect","comments":"5 pages, 5 figures","journal-ref":"Phys.Rev.Lett. 90 (2003) 091303","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.90.091303","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph hep-ph hep-th","license":null,"abstract":"  We study the integrated Sachs-Wolfe (ISW) effect using a model-independent\nparameterization of the dark energy equation of state. Cosmic variance severely\nrestricts the class of models distinguishable from Lambda-CDM. In particular if\nthe present value of the equation of state satisfies w_Q^o <-0.8, the only\ndistinguishable models are those with a rapidly varying equation of state,\ncharacterized by a late transition occurring at redshifts z<3. Due to the\ndegeneracy with other cosmological parameters, models with a slowly varying\nbehavior cannot be differentiated from each other or from a cosmological\nconstant using even cosmic variance-limited CMB measurements. This may place a\nfundamental limit on our understanding of the origin of the presently observed\nacceleration.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 9 Oct 2002 16:20:23 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 27 Jan 2003 14:06:56 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-07"}
